.SH NAME
Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::ExtPrivate \- Bitcoin extended private keys
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto qw(btc_extprv);
\&        use Bitcoin::Crypto::Util qw(generate_mnemonic to_format)
\&
\&        # generate mnemonic words first
\&        my $mnemonic = generate_mnemonic;
\&        print "Your mnemonic is: $mnemonic";
\&
\&        # create ExtPrivateKey from mnemonic (without password)
\&        my $key = btc_extprv\->from_mnemonic($mnemonic);
\&        my $ser_key = to_format [base58 => $key\->to_serialized];
\&        print "Your exported master key is: $ser_key";
\&
\&        # derive child private key
\&        my $path = "m/0\*(Aq";
\&        my $child_key = $key\->derive_key($path);
\&        my $ser_child_key = to_format [base58 => $child_key\->to_serialized];
\&        print "Your exported $path child key is: $ser_child_key";
\&
\&        # create basic keypair
\&        my $basic_private = $child_key\->get_basic_key;
\&        my $basic_public = $child_key\->get_public_key\->get_basic_key;
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This class allows you to create an extended private key instance. Extended keys
can be used to securely generate as many addresses as needed through key
derivation. This allows for long\-term, reusable wallet with a single backup.
.PP
Moreover, you can use an extended private key to:
.IP \(bu 4
generate extended public keys
.IP \(bu 4
derive extended keys using standard bip44 or a custom path
.IP \(bu 4
restore keys from mnemonic codes, seeds and serialized form
.SH INTERFACE
.IX Header "INTERFACE"
.SS Attributes
.IX Subsection "Attributes"
\fInetwork\fR
.IX Subsection "network"
.PP
Instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Network \- current network for this key. Can be
coerced from network id. Default: current default network.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_network\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIpurpose\fR
.IX Subsection "purpose"
.PP
BIP44 purpose which was used to obtain this key. Filled automatically when
deriving an extended key. If the key was not obtained through BIP44 derivation,
this attribute is \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIwriter:\fR \f(CW\*(C`set_purpose\*(C'\fR
.PP
\&\fIclearer:\fR \f(CW\*(C`clear_purpose\*(C'\fR
.PP
\fIdepth\fR
.IX Subsection "depth"
.PP
Integer \- depth of derivation. Default: \f(CW0\fR (master key)
.PP
\fIparent_fingerprint\fR
.IX Subsection "parent_fingerprint"
.PP
Bytestring of length 4 \- fingerprint of the parent key. Default: four zero bytes
.PP
\fIchild_number\fR
.IX Subsection "child_number"
.PP
Integer \- sequence number of the key on the current "depth". Default: \f(CW0\fR
.PP
\fIchain_code\fR
.IX Subsection "chain_code"
.PP
Bytestring of length 32 \- chain code of the extended key.
.SS Methods
.IX Subsection "Methods"
\fInew\fR
.IX Subsection "new"
.PP
Constructor is reserved for internal and advanced use only. Use
"from_mnemonic", "from_seed" or "from_serialized" instead.
.PP
\fIfrom_mnemonic\fR
.IX Subsection "from_mnemonic"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $key_object = $class\->from_mnemonic($mnemonic, $password = \*(Aq\*(Aq, $lang = undef)
.Ve
.PP
Creates a new key from given mnemonic and password.
.PP
Note that technically any password is correct and there\*(Aqs no way to tell if it
was mistaken.
.PP
If you want to validate if \f(CW$mnemonic\fR is a valid mnemonic you must specify
\&\f(CW$lang\fR, e.g. \f(CW\*(Aqen\*(Aq\fR. It will also get rid of any extra whitespace before /
after / in between words.
.PP
If no \f(CW$lang\fR is given then any string passed as \f(CW$mnemonic\fR will produce a
valid key. \fBThis means even adding whitespace (eg. trailing newline) will
produce a different key\fR. Be careful when using this method without \f(CW$lang\fR
argument as you can easily create keys incompatible with other software due to
these whitespace problems.
.PP
This method accepts a secret argument. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret for details.
.PP
Returns a new instance of this class.
.PP
\&\fBImportant note about unicode:\fR this function only accepts UTF8\-decoded
strings (both \f(CW$mnemonic\fR and \f(CW$password\fR), but can\*(Aqt detect whether it got
it or not. This will only become a problem if you use non\-ascii mnemonic and/or
password. If there\*(Aqs a possibility of non\-ascii, always use utf8 and set
binmodes to get decoded (wide) characters to avoid problems recovering your
wallet.
.PP
\fIfrom_seed\fR
.IX Subsection "from_seed"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $key_object = $class\->from_seed($seed)
.Ve
.PP
Creates and returns a new key from seed, which can be any data of any length.
\&\f(CW$seed\fR is expected to be a byte string.
.PP
This method accepts a secret argument. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret for details.
.PP
\fIto_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "to_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $serialized = $object\->to_serialized()
.Ve
.PP
Returns the key serialized in format specified in BIP32 as byte string.
.PP
\fIfrom_serialized\fR
.IX Subsection "from_serialized"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $key_object = $class\->from_serialized($serialized, $network = undef)
.Ve
.PP
Tries to unserialize byte string \f(CW$serialized\fR with format specified in BIP32.
.PP
Dies on errors. If multiple networks match serialized data specify \f(CW$network\fR
manually (id of the network) to avoid exception.
.PP
This method accepts a secret argument. See Bitcoin::Crypto::Secret for details.
.PP
\fIset_network\fR
.IX Subsection "set_network"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $object\->set_network($val)
.Ve
.PP
Change key\*(Aqs network state to \f(CW$val\fR. It can be either network name present in
Bitcoin::Crypto::Network package or an instance of this class.
.PP
\fIget_public_key\fR
.IX Subsection "get_public_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $public_key_object = $object\->get_public_key()
.Ve
.PP
Returns instance of Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::ExtPublic generated from the
private key.
.PP
\fIget_basic_key\fR
.IX Subsection "get_basic_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $basic_key_object = $object\->get_basic_key()
.Ve
.PP
Returns the key in basic format: Bitcoin::Crypto::Key::Private
.PP
\fIderive_key\fR
.IX Subsection "derive_key"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $derived_key_object = $object\->derive_key($path)
.Ve
.PP
Performs extended key derivation as specified in BIP32 on the current key with
\&\f(CW$path\fR. Dies on error.
.PP
See BIP32 document for details on derivation paths and methods.
.PP
Returns a new extended key instance \- result of a derivation.
.PP
\fIderive_key_bip44\fR
.IX Subsection "derive_key_bip44"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $derived_key_object = $object\->derive_key_bip44(%data)
.Ve
.PP
A helper that constructs a Bitcoin::Crypto::BIP44 path from \f(CW%data\fR and
calls "derive_key" with it. Refer to "Attributes" in Bitcoin::Crypto::BIP44 to
see what you can include in \f(CW%data\fR.
.PP
Using this method instead of specifying BIP44 path yourself will make sure all
features of BIP44 derivation will be enabled, like different prefixes for
extended keys (\f(CW\*(C`xprv\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`yprv\*(C'\fR / \f(CW\*(C`zprv\*(C'\fR) and address type generation
checking.
.PP
\&\fINote: coin_type parameter will be ignored, and the current network
configuration set in the extended key will be used.\fR
.PP
\fIget_fingerprint\fR
.IX Subsection "get_fingerprint"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        $fingerprint = $object\->get_fingerprint($len = 4)
.Ve
.PP
Returns a fingerprint of the extended key of \f(CW$len\fR length (byte string)
